{"name":"Period finding","description":"\nShor's period-finding algorithm a quantum algorithm introduced in [[1994, Shor]](https://doi.org/10.1109/sfcs.1994.365700) to solve the following problem.\n\n**Problem**. Let $f : \\NN \\to \\\\{ 0, \\ldots, N - 1 \\\\}$ be a function with the property that there is some unknown $r \\in \\\\{ 0, \\ldots, N - 1 \\\\}$ such that $f(a) = f(b)$ if and only if $a \\equiv b \\mod r$. Determine $r$.\n\n<details>\n<summary>Shor's period-finding algorithm</summary>\n\nLet $n = \\lceil \\log_2 N \\rceil$ and choose $M = 2^m$ such that $N^2 < M \\le 2 N^2$. Denote by $\\mathcal{O}$ the oracle on $(m + n)$ qubits that acts as $\\mathcal{O} \\left( \\ket{a} \\otimes \\ket{0^n} \\right) \\mapsto \\ket{a} \\otimes \\ket{f(a)}$.\n\n1. Start with the $(m + n)$-qubit state $\\ket{0^m} \\otimes \\ket{0^n}$.\n2. Apply the quantum Fourier transform $F_M$ to obtain the state $\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{M}} \\sum_{a = 0}^{M - 1} \\ket{a} \\otimes \\ket{0^n}$. Alternatively, the same result can be achieved by applying a Hadamard gate to the first $m$ qubits.\n3. Apply $\\mathcal{O}$ to obtain the state $\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{M}} \\sum_{a = 0}^{M - 1} \\ket{a} \\otimes \\ket{f(a)}$.\n4. Measure the second register to obtain some $f(s)$. Since $f$ has period $r$, we may assume $s < r$. Ignoring from now on the second register, the state collapses to $\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{K}} \\sum_{k = 0}^{K} \\ket{s + kr}$ for some $K$.\n5. Apply the quantum Fourier transform $F_M$ to obtain the state $$ \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{K}} \\sum_{k = 0}^{K - 1} \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{M}} \\sum_{a = 0}^{M - 1} \\exp \\left( 2 \\pi i \\frac{(s + kr) a}{M} \\right) \\ket{a} = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{K M}} \\sum_{a = 0}^{M - 1} \\exp \\left( 2 \\pi i \\frac{s a}{M} \\right) \\sum_{k = 0}^{K} \\exp \\left( 2 \\pi i \\frac{k r a}{M} \\right) \\ket{a} $$ and note that\n$$ \\sum_{k = 0}^{K - 1} \\exp \\left( 2 \\pi i \\frac{k r a}{M} \\right) = \\begin{cases} K & \\textup{ if } \\exp \\left( 2 \\pi i \\right) = 1 , \\\\ \\frac{1 - \\exp(2 \\pi i \\tfrac{K r a}{M})}{1 - \\exp(2 \\pi i \\tfrac{r a}{M})} & \\textup{ if } \\exp \\left( 2 \\pi i \\right) \\ne 1 . \\\\ \\end{cases} $$\n6. Measure the state to obtain some $a$. It can be shown that, with high probability, the value $a$ will be such that $$ \\left| \\frac{a}{M} - \\frac{c}{r} \\right| \\le \\frac{1}{2 M} $$ for some $0 \\le c < r$. In that case, since $r \\le N$ and $N^2 < M$, there can be at most \\textit{one} such fraction $c / r$ satisfying the above inequality. Hence, $c / r$ can be obtained classically as the fraction with denominator $\\le N$ that is closest to $a / M$ (e.g. using a contined-fraction expansion). Moreover, with high probability $c$ will be coprime to $r$, so that $r$ is precisely the denominator of the obtained fraction written in reduced form.\n</details>\n\n**Experiment**. Given an integer $n \\ge 2$, a period $r$ is defined as the largest prime number less than $N = 2^n$. The task is to determine $r$ by applying Shor's factoring algorithm to the function $f(a) = a \\mod r$. The circuit is run for $1,000$ shots.\n\n**Metrics**. The _accuracy_ is defined as the fraction of shots that result in the correct estimate of $r$. Note that shots resulting in $a = 0$ are disregarded, as no estimate for $r$ can be derived from it.\n","params":{"n":"int"},"metrics":["accuracy"],"data":[{"backend":"aer","n":2,"circuit_depths":[110],"circuit_widths":[8],"circuit_gates":[{"cp":102,"h":48,"ccx":8,"u2":8,"measure":4}],"runtime":0.002401113510131836,"accuracy":0.8560250391236307,"entropy":0.6318152717366833},{"backend":"ibm_aachen","n":2,"circuit_depths":[1250],"circuit_widths":[8],"circuit_gates":[{"sx":946,"rz":596,"cz":472,"x":24,"measure":4}],"transpile_time":0.03011804199195467,"qpu_time":1.22273,"runtime":1.2528480419919548,"accuracy":0.271474019088017,"entropy":0.9789424006669959},{"backend":"ibm_brussels","n":2,"circuit_depths":[1613],"circuit_widths":[8],"circuit_gates":[{"rz":1341,"sx":776,"ecr":478,"x":86,